      "showLabel": true,
      "data": {
        "title": "Typography System Contract",
        "localTitle": "Typography System Contract",
        "publishedTitle": "Typography System Contract",
        "purpose": "Summarize the typography doctrine into one readable document surface.",
        "titleSourceNodeId": "typography-contract-title",
        "audience": "Reader",
        "status": "active",
        "viewRole": "document",
        "viewKind": "display",
        "exposedAuthority": "consume-view",
        "runtimeExposed": false,
        "partNodeIds": [
          "typography-contract-title",
          "typography-contract-problem",
          "typography-contract-roles",
          "typography-contract-rules",
          "typography-contract-adoption",
          "typography-contract-summary"
        ],
        "documentOrder": [
          "typography-contract-title",
          "typography-contract-problem",
          "typography-contract-roles",
          "typography-contract-rules",
          "typography-contract-adoption",
          "typography-contract-summary"
        ],
        "documentHtml": "<section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;box-sizing:border-box;padding:22px;border-radius:20px;background:linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(248,250,252,0.99), rgba(241,245,249,0.96));border:1px solid rgba(71,85,105,0.18);box-shadow:0 12px 28px rgba(15,23,42,0.10);gap:14px;\"><div style=\"font:700 11px/1.2 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;letter-spacing:0.18em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#475569;\">Title</div><div style=\"font:700 30px/1.08 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Typography System Contract</div><div style=\"height:1px;background:linear-gradient(90deg, rgba(100,116,139,0.45), rgba(100,116,139,0));\"></div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.65 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#475569;\">Twilite needs a real type contract: stable roles, shared tokens, and fewer local styling guesses.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Problem Statement</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">Twilite currently has color themes, but not a typography system. Many node classes and editor surfaces choose font size, weight, family, and spacing locally. The result is legible but not governed, and quality depends too much on one-off styling decisions.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Core Type Roles</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">The system should define a small set of shared roles: display, title, body, label, meta, and mono. Display handles strong document and landing statements. Title handles card and section headers. Body handles readable prose. Label and meta handle UI chrome and status language. Mono is reserved for code, ids, and machine-facing output.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">System Rules</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">Typography decisions should live in the theme and shared tokens first, not in arbitrary local styles. Local overrides are acceptable only when the surface has a clear semantic reason. Browser chrome, task/document nodes, reference surfaces, and edge labels should all read from the same role vocabulary before specialty nodes are tuned individually.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0 0 20px 0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:20px;border-radius:20px;background:#fff;border:1px solid rgba(15,23,42,0.12);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#111827;\">Adoption Order</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.7 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1f2937;\">Adopt the system in layers. First define theme-level typography tokens and family strategy. Then apply those roles to browser/editor chrome, task and summary surfaces, reference surfaces, and edge labels. Only after the shared surfaces are stable should specialty utility nodes receive their own tuned exceptions.</div></div></section><section style=\"margin:0;\"><div style=\"display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:12px;padding:22px 24px;border-radius:18px;background:linear-gradient(180deg, rgba(239,246,255,0.98), rgba(224,231,255,0.98));border:1px solid rgba(59,130,246,0.16);\"><div style=\"font:700 24px/1.15 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1d4ed8;\">Summary</div><div style=\"font:500 15px/1.75 ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;color:#1e3a8a;\">Twilite needs a typography contract, not just fonts. The system should define shared roles, move primary decisions into theme-level tokens, limit local overrides, and adopt the shared language across browser chrome and common node surfaces before tuning specialty nodes.</div></div></section>",
        "_classBinding": {
          "key": "document-view",
          "sourceRef": "github://twilite-zone/public/library/classes/nodes/ui-interaction/document-view.node-class.node",
